<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14090">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Energy.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13166">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13166 mb-requirement-id-13167">
        (a) With your parent or guardian's permission, use the internet to find
        a blog, podcast, website, or an article on the use or conservation of
        energy. Discuss with your counselor what details in the article were
        interesting to you, the questions it raises, and what ideas it addresses
        that you do not understand. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ytwIzy3XuGg" target="_blank"
          >The Essentials of Energy (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/CW0_S5YpYVo" target="_blank"
          >World's Most Asked Questions: What Is Energy? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13166 mb-requirement-id-13168">
        (b) After you have completed requirements 2 through 8, revisit your
        source for requirement 1(a). Explain to your counselor what you have
        learned in completing the requirements that helps you better understand
        the article.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13169">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Show you understand energy forms and conversions by doing the following:
      <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/mA7aYNCpHdg" target="_blank"
        >Different Forms of Energy (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/5UL_FX5wCH4" target="_blank"
        >Energy Transformations (video)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13169 mb-requirement-id-13170">
        (a) Explain how THREE of the following devices use energy, and explain
        their energy conversions: toaster, greenhouse, lightbulb, bow drill,
        cell phone, nuclear reactor, sauna, or electric vehicles. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/s5gufMXDg9M" target="_blank"
          >How Does a Toaster Work? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/KI-Wf2odCqM" target="_blank"
          >How Do Greenhouses Work? Easy Explanation! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/oCEKMEeZXug" target="_blank"
          >How Modern Light Bulbs Work (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ZEl-Y1NvBVI" target="_blank"
          >Primitive Technology: Cord Drill and Pump Drill (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/AYgxeSvPXK4" target="_blank"
          >How Wireless Charging REALLY Works! (The Hidden Physics) (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Ta3z3pGK0vU" target="_blank"
          >What Is Nuclear Energy? | National Geographic (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/734-EmRGYPI" target="_blank"
          >ICE vs. Electric: The Future of Driving Compared (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13169 mb-requirement-id-13171">
        (b) Construct a system that makes at least two energy conversions and
        explain this to your counselor. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/VQqpnAKf9cM" target="_blank"
          >Solar Motor-Free Energy Motor (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/DcZkmj1afZs" target="_blank"
          >Solar Powered Toy Bell Ringer (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/P6al80Gv4wg" target="_blank"
          >How to Make a Simple Windmill for Free Energy - School Project |
          Functional (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/-1xsyt4T6eU" target="_blank"
          >How to Make a Free Energy Using Water Wheel - Science Project Without
          Electricity (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13172">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Show you understand energy efficiency by explaining to your counselor a
      common example of a situation where energy moves through a system to
      produce a useful result. Do the following: <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/gWil5xVfwqw" target="_blank"
        >Energy Transfers in Appliances (video)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13172 mb-requirement-id-13173">
        (a) Identify the parts of the system that are affected by the energy
        movement.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13172 mb-requirement-id-13174">
        (b) Name the system's primary source of energy.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13172 mb-requirement-id-13175">
        (c) Identify the useful outcomes of the system.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13172 mb-requirement-id-13176">
        (d) Identify the energy losses of the system.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13177">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Conduct an energy audit of your home. Keep a 14 day log that records what
      you and your family did to reduce energy use. Include the following in
      your report and, after the 14-day period, discuss what you have learned
      with your counselor. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/YolBP0-vkBU" target="_blank"
        >Energy 101: Home Energy Assessment (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://www.energy.gov/energysaver/do-it-yourself-home-energy-assessments"
        target="_blank"
        >Do-It-Yourself Home Energy Assessments (website)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://www.seattle.gov/Documents/Departments/OSE/GreenHomeGuide-FYIenergyaudit.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >Do It Yourself Home Energy Audit Form (PDF)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13177 mb-requirement-id-13178">
        (a) List the types of energy used in your home such as electricity,
        wood, oil, liquid petroleum, and natural gas, and tell how each is
        delivered and measured, and the current cost; OR record the
        transportation fuel used, miles driven, miles per gallon, and trips
        using your family car or another vehicle. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/use-of-energy/homes.php"
          target="_blank"
          >Use of Energy Explained - Energy Use in Homes (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13177 mb-requirement-id-13179">
        (b) Describe ways you and your family can use energy resources more
        wisely. In preparing your discussion, consider the energy required for
        the things you do and use on a daily basis (cooking, showering, using
        lights, driving, watching TV, using the computer). Explain what is meant
        by sustainable energy sources. Explain how you can change your energy
        use through reuse and recycling. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AKcfc2WXIWY" target="_blank"
          >Save Energy (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://carbon-calculator.climatehero.org/" target="_blank"
          >Environmental Footprint Calculator (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/J_iDcKDAwbA" target="_blank"
          >Your Carbon Footprint (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1kUE0BZtTRc" target="_blank"
          >Renewable Energy 101 (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/uCDOm4AcPQk" target="_blank"
          >Reduce, Reuse, Recycle (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13180">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      In a notebook, identify and describe five examples of energy waste in your
      school or community. Suggest in each case possible ways to reduce this
      waste. Describe the idea of trade-offs in energy use. In your response, do
      the following: <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/QsAgaD7IeuA" target="_blank"
        >The Surprising Places We Waste Energy (video)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13180 mb-requirement-id-13181">
        (a) Explain how the changes you suggest would lower costs, reduce
        pollution, or otherwise improve your community.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13180 mb-requirement-id-13182">
        (b) Explain what changes to routines, habits, or convenience are
        necessary to reduce energy waste. Tell why people might resist the
        changes you suggest. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.un.org/en/actnow/ten-actions#:~:text=Use%20less%20energy%20by%20reducing,instead%20of%20using%20a%20dryer."
          target="_blank"
          >Actions for a Healthy Planet (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13183">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Prepare pie charts showing the following information, and explain to your
      counselor the important ideas each chart reveals. Tell where you got your
      information. Explain how cost affects the use of a nonrenewable energy
      resource and makes alternatives practical.
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13183 mb-requirement-id-13184">
        (a) The energy resources that supply the United States with most of its
        energy <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.eia.gov/totalenergy/data/monthly/pdf/flow/total_energy_spaghettichart_2024.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >U.S. Energy Consumption by Source and Sector, 2024 (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/OBuAzxp3EE0" target="_blank"
          >Everything You Need to Know About the Energy Flowcharts (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.eia.gov/totalenergy/data/monthly/" target="_blank"
          >Monthly Energy Review (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13183 mb-requirement-id-13185">
        (b) The share of energy resources used by the United States that comes
        from other countries <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/evIAnt5mNGI" target="_blank"
          >Why Does the US Import Oil When They Export So Much? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail.php?id=65664"
          target="_blank"
          >US Energy Imports and Exports (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13183 mb-requirement-id-13186">
        (c) The proportion of energy resources used by homes, businesses,
        industry, and transportation <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/use-of-energy/"
          target="_blank"
          >Use of Energy Explained (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/" target="_blank"
          >Energy Consumption &amp; Efficiency Data | Energy Information Agency
          (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13183 mb-requirement-id-13187">
        (d) The fuels used to generate America's electricity <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://www.eia.gov/totalenergy/data/browser/index.php?tbl=T01.03#/?f=A"
          target="_blank"
          >Total Energy: Primary Energy Consumption by Source (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13183 mb-requirement-id-13188">
        (e) The world's known and estimated primary energy resource reserves
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.eia.gov/international/overview/world"
          target="_blank"
          >International Data (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13189">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      Tell what is being done to make FIVE of the following energy systems
      produce more usable energy. In your explanation, describe the technology,
      cost, environmental impacts, and safety concerns. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/Z8JFCJP70rg" target="_blank"
        >How Cheap Renewable Energy Is Finally Flattening Emissions (video)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13191">
        (a) Biomass digesters or waste-to-energy plants <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/cxvl24c_oeQ" target="_blank"
          >Flexible Clean Energy: Powering Tomorrow With Biomass (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13192">
        (b) Cogeneration plants <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/P-sMnC8CxI8" target="_blank"
          >The Combined Cycle Gas Turbine - the World's Most Efficient Power
          Machine (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13193">
        (c) Fossil fuel power plants <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/TGppuZZosxQ" target="_blank"
          >From Coal to Clean Energy: A Utility-Scale Milestone in New Mexico
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/XSsiohv0DLc" target="_blank"
          >How Forsite Development Transforms Retired Coal Sites Into Clean
          Solar Energy Hubs (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13194">
        (d) Fuel cells <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/6tvvsCxBfeM" target="_blank"
          >Fuel Cell Technology - the Future of Clean Energy (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13195">
        (e) Geothermal power plants <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/eWkhpWRRpVo" target="_blank"
          >The Secret Behind Iceland's Geothermal Energy (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/rqkJiMDAIpA" target="_blank"
          >Should We Build A Geothermal Power Plant In Yellowstone? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13196">
        (f) Nuclear power plants <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/jRYUjQw5fWE" target="_blank"
          >The Path to a New Era for Nuclear Energy (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/xKeCmpZ0-U4" target="_blank"
          >How Close Are We to Nuclear Fusion? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13197">
        (g) Solar power systems <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/tQmFVcD-Mbo" target="_blank"
          >Solar 3.0: This New Technology Could Change Everything (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13198">
        (h) Tidal energy, wave energy, or ocean thermal energy conversion
        devices <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/HsyIbzIiaBM" target="_blank"
          >OTEC: The Huge Ocean Energy Source You've Never Heard of (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13189 mb-requirement-id-13199">
        (i) Wind turbines <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9tJjDQ-X2mo" target="_blank"
          >Wind Power Advances: Cutting-Edge Technologies Shaping the Future
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13190">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 8. </span>
      Identify three career opportunities that would use skills and knowledge in
      energy. Pick one and research the training, education, certification
      requirements, experience, and expenses associated with entering the field.
      Research the prospects for employment, starting salary, advancement
      opportunities, and career goals associated with this career. Discuss what
      you learned with your counselor and whether you might be interested in
      this career. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/jBZ3vurfhXM" target="_blank"
        >Careers in Energy and Natural Resources (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://www.energy.gov/ne/articles/7-nuclear-careers-dont-require-engineering-degree"
        target="_blank"
        >7 Nuclear Careers that Don't Require an Engineering Degree (PDF)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
